	<h3>Top Barcelona Tourist Spots</h3>
<p>To start off, here are some of the most famous tourist spots in Barcelona:</p>
<h4>La Sagrada Familia</h4>
<figure id="attachment_18042" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-18042" style="width: 830px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-18042" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Sagrada_Familia.jpg" alt="Sagrada Familia" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Sagrada_Familia.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Sagrada_Familia-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Sagrada_Familia-768x490.jpg 768w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Sagrada_Familia-470x300.jpg 470w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-18042" class="wp-caption-text">Sagrada Familia</figcaption></figure>
<p>This Basilica of the Holy Family popularly known as <a href="https://spainguides.com/spain-travel/a-guided-tour-of-the-sagrada-familia-barcelonas-brightest-gem/">La Sagrada Família</a> is a must-visit while in Barcelona. This famed Basilica started construction in March 1882 and is still under construction even to this date. It was designed by the world-famous architect known as Antoni Gaudi and was declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2005.</p>
<p>The architectural design of the building with special attention to the different facades and carvings on the exterior, coupled with its towering spires is something that one definitely cannot afford to miss.</p>
<p>The interior of the basilica is equally beautiful with the tall pillars that form a canopy like that of a forest while the stained glass windows give the space a colourful hue.</p>
<p>Take an elevator to one of the towers to get a magnificent bird’s eye view of Barcelona city.</p>
<p>La Sagrada Familiar can get very busy at peak times of the year so if you do plan to visit then it's certainly best to book your entry tickets well in advance which will save you time and money.  Sites such as <a href="https://www.hellotickets.com/spain/barcelona/sagrada-familia-skip-the-line-tickets/sc-122-869" target="_blank" rel="noopener">HelloTickets</a>, Get Your Guide, and Tiqets are good for booking tours and entry tickets.</p>
<h4>Park Guell</h4>
<p><img decoding="async" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-15568" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/Parc-Guell.jpg" alt="Parc Guell Barcelona" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/Parc-Guell.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/Parc-Guell-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/Parc-Guell-768x490.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /></p>
<p>Another creation by Gaudi is Park Güell which is full of colours in the mosaics on the benches, snakes curves and trees and plants. Located on a hill that is called Carmel Hill, the park offers a spectacular 360-degree view of the city.</p>
<p>Initially conceived as a housing development, <a href="https://spainguides.com/parc-guell-barcelona-a-special-guadi-masterpiece/">Park Guell</a> is now a public park which demonstrates Gaudí’s architectural style that harmonises the man-made with the natural environment.</p>
<p>The multicolours mosaic of lizards known as “El Drac” in the entrance of the park is always a good area for photography. Strolling through the park, it is possible to admire the elements of Gaudí’s architecture such as the Hypostyle Room and the beautiful viaducts.</p>
<h4>La Rambla</h4>
<p><img decoding="async" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-17286" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Las-Ramblas.jpg" alt="Las Ramblas Barcelona" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Las-Ramblas.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Las-Ramblas-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Las-Ramblas-768x490.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /></p>
<p>La Rambla is one of the main roads of the city of Barcelona which has street performers, market stalls, cafes and stores. It covers from Plaça de Catalunya to Christopher Columbus Monument and it is a great place to enjoy the spirit of this city.</p>
<p>This famous boulevard is lined with landmarks, including the Gran Teatre del Liceu which is one of the leading opera houses in Europe as well as the colourful <a href="https://www.boqueria.barcelona/home" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Mercat de Sant Josep de la Boqueria</a> where people can taste famous Catalan cuisine.</p>
<p>Nevertheless, the atmosphere of the locals can still be felt along the La Rambla even in the side streets where one can find small bars and restaurants.</p>
<h4>Gothic Quarter</h4>
<figure id="attachment_2139" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-2139" style="width: 830px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-2139" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/barcelona-gothic-quarter.jpg" alt="Barcelona Gothic Quarter" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/barcelona-gothic-quarter.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/barcelona-gothic-quarter-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/barcelona-gothic-quarter-768x490.jpg 768w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/barcelona-gothic-quarter-600x384.jpg 600w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-2139" class="wp-caption-text">Barcelona Gothic Quarter</figcaption></figure>
<p>The Barri Gothic also known as the Gothic Quarter is a medieval city with twisting and winding streets and alleys. It is possible to visit ancient Roman ruins, beautiful cathedrals, for example, Barcelona Cathedral and small cosy squares with cafes and shops.</p>
<p>Meandering the back streets of the Gothic Quarter is a great place to find beautifully designed courtyards, small shops and cosy bars. The Plaça Reial with beautiful palm trees and a lovely vibrant atmosphere at night, is one of the most stunning squares in the city.</p>
<h4>Casa Batllo and Casa Mila</h4>
<figure id="attachment_14243" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-14243" style="width: 830px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-14243" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/Casa-Batllo-4.jpg" alt="Casa Batllo Barcelona" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/Casa-Batllo-4.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/Casa-Batllo-4-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/Casa-Batllo-4-768x490.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-14243" class="wp-caption-text">Casa Batllo Barcelona</figcaption></figure>
<p>These two buildings, namely <a href="https://spainguides.com/spain-travel/casa-batllo-awarded-worlds-best-landmark-2021/">Casa Batllo</a> and Casa Mila or La Pedrera are considered as Gaudi’s masterpiece.</p>
<p>Both of these architectural marvels are situated on the world-famous Passeig de Gracia and are characterised by their intricate exterior and interior design.</p>
<p>The colourful house with tiles and organic shapes was nicknamed the House of Bones because of the design resembling a skeleton. On the other hand, <a href="https://spainguides.com/visiting-casa-mila-la-pedrera-all-you-need-to-know/">Casa Mila</a> has a stone façade that has an undulating design as well as wrought iron balconies that also give a feeling of movement.</p>
<p>Both buildings are open for the tour with a view of the rooftop where you can get an overview of the building having strange-shaped chimneys at Casa Milà.</p>
<h4>Montjuic Hill</h4>
<p><img decoding="async" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-13475" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/Barcelone-Montjuic-Park.jpg" alt="Montjuic Park" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/Barcelone-Montjuic-Park.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/Barcelone-Montjuic-Park-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/Barcelone-Montjuic-Park-768x490.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /></p>
<p>Montjuïc Hill is one of the most popular tourist attraction centres that gives a beautiful view of the city of Barcelona and the coast.</p>
<p>Some of the places that are of interest include the Montjuïc Castle, the Magic Fountain and the National Art Museum of Catalonia (MNAC). Some of the pieces of art on display at the MNAC include Romanesque, Gothic and modern art as well as works of art by famous Catalan artists.</p>
<p>Another <a href="https://poble-espanyol.com/en/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">famous place of Montjuic is the Poble Espanyol</a> – the live museum with the architecture of different Spanish regions. The hill was very important during the 1992 Summer Olympics and there are still remnants of the facilities for the Olympic games on the hill.</p>
<h4>Camp Nou</h4>
<p><img decoding="async" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-16414" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Barcelona_FC.jpg" alt="Barcelona Football Club Tour" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Barcelona_FC.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Barcelona_FC-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Barcelona_FC-768x490.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /></p>
<p>Fans of football should not be left empty-handed when in Barcelona as they can pay a visit to the Camp Nou Stadium which is home to <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/FC-Barcelona">FC Barcelona</a>.</p>
<p>A perfect way to explore the whole stadium is by joining one of the recommended in-house <a href="https://spainguides.com/visit-barcelona-football-club-camp-nou-stadium-museum/">stadium tours</a> where you visit the museum, the trophy room and even get to walk through the pitch.</p>
<p>Several touchscreen displays and interactive stations give a detailed insight into the club’s history and such players as Johan Cruijff, <a href="https://www.instagram.com/leomessi/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Lionel Messi</a> and Xavi Hernandez.</p>
<p>During the matches, the spirit of the fans at Camp Nou is always high, with supporters from different parts of the globe coming to support their favourite team. Non-football fans can also enjoy the atmosphere and tradition of this famous stadium and its surroundings.</p>
<h4>Barceloneta Beach</h4>
<p><img decoding="async" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-15270" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/Hotel-W-Barcelona.jpg" alt="Hotel W Barcelona" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/Hotel-W-Barcelona.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/Hotel-W-Barcelona-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/Hotel-W-Barcelona-768x490.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /></p>
<p>Barceloneta Beach is a beach located in Barcelona and is known to be the most popular beach where people can swim, sunbathe or eat seafood at the various beachside restaurants and chiringuitos.</p>
<p>There is plenty to do on Barceloneta Beach such as a range of water sports including windsurfing, paddle boarding as well as kayaking.</p>
<p>Barceloneta is also famous for its vibrant night activities since there are many bars and clubs which are located along the promenade.</p>
