	<h3>Free things to do in Barcelona</h3>
<p><img decoding="async" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-15570" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/Parc-Guell-Barcelona.jpg" alt="Parc Guell Barcelona" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/Parc-Guell-Barcelona.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/Parc-Guell-Barcelona-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/Parc-Guell-Barcelona-768x490.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /></p>
<p>If your travelling on a tight budget there are plenty of things to do in Barcelona completely for FREE!.</p>
<p>You can stroll along Las Ramblas, soaking in the vibrant street life and performances, or wander through the Gothic Quarter, where you'll discover stunning architecture and hidden squares.</p>
<p>Head to Park Guell for free entry to certain areas, or enjoy the sprawling green spaces of Montjuic, offering panoramic city views.</p>
<p>Beach lovers can relax at the city's many beaches, like Barceloneta, without spending a penny.</p>
<p>Cultural hotspots like El Born Cultural Center offer free entry and exhibitions on specific days, while the <a href="https://museupicassobcn.cat/en" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Picasso Museum</a> provides free entry on Sundays after 3 pm. You can also explore many of Barcelona’s beautiful churches, like the <a href="https://catedralbcn.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Barcelona Cathedral</a>, free of charge.</p>
<p>Take a scenic walk through Ciutadella Park, where you can relax by its beautiful fountain or row a boat in its small lake.</p>
<p>Nature enthusiasts can also explore the <a href="https://parcnaturalcollserola.cat/en/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Collserola Natural Park</a>, a short journey from the city, perfect for hiking and panoramic views.</p>
<p>For a cultural touch, attend some of the <a href="https://spainguides.com/best-festivals-in-spain/">many festivals held throughout the year</a>, like La Merce, featuring concerts and street performances across the city.</p>
<p>Don’t forget to explore the famed food markets such as  Mercat de Sant Antoni or La Boqueria Market, these are great places to experience the vibrant food culture without spending anything.</p>
<h3>Tips for Foodie Enthusiasts</h3>
<figure id="attachment_19061" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-19061" style="width: 830px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-19061" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Crema-Catalana.jpg" alt="Crema Catalana" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Crema-Catalana.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Crema-Catalana-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Crema-Catalana-768x490.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-19061" class="wp-caption-text">Crema Catalana</figcaption></figure>
<p>When it comes to <a href="https://spainguides.com/spain-travel/gastronomy/spanish-food/">food</a>, Barcelona is a food lovers’ paradise as it has a number of traditional as well as modern food which is served in the city.</p>
<p>While you are in the city, do not only limit yourself to the famous foods and restaurants that tourists usually visit.</p>
<p>Some of them are pa amb tomàquet (bread with tomato), escalivada (grilled vegetables) and crema catalana (Catalonian cream). These dishes are examples of the culinary traditions of the region and are still popular in local restaurants.</p>
<p>Tapas bars are a must-visit, which serve plenty of small plates of food, suitable for 2-3 persons.</p>
<p>It is recommended to order several tapas for example patatas bravas which are crispy potatoes served with spicy tomato sauce and aioli sauce and boquerones which are marinated anchovies.</p>
<p>For dessert, you can have churros con chocolate a Spanish delicacy where you have deep-fried dough with chocolate sauce. It’s also important to eat turron, a kind of nougat with almonds and honey that is found in many types and which is especially consumed during the Christmas period.</p>
<h4>Barcelona Eateries You Should Try</h4>
<figure id="attachment_2746" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-2746" style="width: 830px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-2746" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Paella-Seafood.jpg" alt="Seafood Paella Spain" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Paella-Seafood.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Paella-Seafood-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Paella-Seafood-768x490.jpg 768w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Paella-Seafood-600x383.jpg 600w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Paella-Seafood-800x510.jpg 800w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Paella-Seafood-400x255.jpg 400w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-2746" class="wp-caption-text">Seafood Paella</figcaption></figure>
<p>For authentic Catalonian cuisine, <a href="https://culleretes.com/en/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Can Culleretes</a> in the Gothic Quarter of Barcelona is a historic spot that’s been serving traditional dishes since 1786, making it the oldest restaurant in the city. Here, you can try classic Catalan dishes like <em>escudella i carn d'olla</em> (a traditional meat stew).</p>
<p>Another great place is <a href="https://7portes.com/en/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">7 Portes</a>, located near Barceloneta. This elegant restaurant is famous for its <em>paella</em> and seafood, offering a fine taste of Mediterranean flavours combined with Catalan culinary traditions.</p>
<p>In the Eixample district, <a href="https://cincsentits.com/en/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Cinc Sentits</a> offers a modern take on Catalonian cuisine. This award winning 2 Michelin-starred restaurant is known for seasonal dishes using locally sourced ingredients, reflecting the rich diversity of the region's produce.</p>
<p><a href="https://elglop.com/en/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">El Glop</a> in Gracia is a must-visit for rustic Catalan cuisine, specializing in <em>calçots</em> (grilled green onions) and grilled meats, providing a hearty, authentic experience.</p>
<p>Finally, <a href="https://www.lavinyadelsenyor.es/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">La Vinya del Senyor</a> in El Born is perfect for enjoying traditional Catalonian tapas paired with a fantastic selection of local wines. Located right by the Santa Maria del Mar church, it’s a charming spot to immerse yourself in the flavours of the region.</p>
<h3>Packing Essentials</h3>
<p>Barcelona has a Mediterranean climate so it has mild winters and hot summers and that is why it is advisable to pack right.</p>
<p>For the summer period which is from June to August, you should pack light and loose-fitting clothes, sunglasses and a hat to shield you from the sun.</p>
<p>Do not forget some comfortable shoes because you will be spending most of your time walking around the city. For the winter months of December, January and February, it is recommended to pack a light jacket and layers as the climate can be chilly, especially during the night.</p>
<p>No matter the time of the year, reusable bottle-filled water is necessary to have when moving around. A small body pack is also advisable to carry around with you to keep your valuables as well as any items you purchase.</p>
<p>Its always a good idea to check <a href="https://spainguides.com/weather/">what the usual Barcelona weather will be like</a> during the time you wish to stay here.</p>
<h3>Safety Advice</h3>
<p>The city of Barcelona is generally safe for tourists however, tourists should always take some caution to avoid adverse incidents.</p>
<p>Petty theft such as pickpocketing can be a problem, especially in places with a lot of people such as tourist destinations and transport facilities.</p>
<p>We highly recommend using a cross-body bag or a money belt where you can safely keep your valuable items.</p>
<p>Most importantly when visiting Barcelona, remember to stay respectful of the local customs and have fun!</p>
