<div class="siteorigin-widget-tinymce textwidget">
	<h4>Let`s take a look at the big 10 Spanish Cities you should visit:</h4>
<h3>Barcelona</h3>
<figure id="attachment_22423" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-22423" style="width: 830px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="wp-image-22423 size-full" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Gracia-District-Barcelona.jpg" alt="Gracia District Barcelona" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Gracia-District-Barcelona.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Gracia-District-Barcelona-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Gracia-District-Barcelona-768x490.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-22423" class="wp-caption-text">Gracia District Barcelona</figcaption></figure>
<p>Barcelona, is the ultimate urban getaway in Spain.  With its stunning architecture, unique atmosphere, and delicious food offerings, <a href="https://spainguides.com/spain-travel/things-to-do-in-barcelona/">Barcelona offers something for every urban traveller</a>.</p>
<p>Imagine wandering through the labyrinthine streets of the Gothic Quarter, stumbling upon hidden gems and admiring iconic landmarks like the Sagrada Familia.</p>
<p>Experience Barcelona's rich history and culture by visiting world-class museums, attending live music performances, or exploring the vibrant local markets.</p>
<p>When the sun shines, head to one of Barcelona's beautiful beaches, such as Barceloneta or Bogatell. Soak up the Mediterranean sunshine, take a gentle dip or simply relax on the sand.</p>
<p>And when night falls, Barcelona's nightlife comes alive. Dance the night away in the some of trendiest clubs in Spain, enjoy live music at bars, or sip cocktails on rooftop terraces with panoramic city views.</p>
<p>Indulge your taste buds with Catalan cuisine, known for its fresh seafood, hearty stews, and delicious tapas. Don't miss the opportunity to chill out in one of <a href="https://spainguides.com/spain-travel/best-coffee-shops-in-barcelona/">Barcelona’s famed coffee shops</a> or try local specialities like Pan Con Tomate and churros.</p>
<h3>Madrid</h3>
<figure id="attachment_22343" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-22343" style="width: 830px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="wp-image-22343 size-full" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Malasana-District-Madrid.jpg" alt="Malasana District Madrid" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Malasana-District-Madrid.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Malasana-District-Madrid-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Malasana-District-Madrid-768x490.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-22343" class="wp-caption-text">Malasana District Madrid</figcaption></figure>
<p><a href="https://spainguides.com/spain-travel/what-to-see-in-madrid/">Madrid, the vibrant capital of Spain</a>, is a city that pulsates with energy and history. It's a perfect destination for urban travellers seeking a mix of cultural experiences, delicious cuisine, and lively nightlife.</p>
<p>Discover the city by exploring iconic landmarks like the Royal Palace, the Prado Museum, and the Retiro Park.</p>
<p>Immerse yourself in the vibrant atmosphere of the Gran Vía, Madrid's bustling main street, lined with shops, restaurants, and theatres.</p>
<p>Madrid is a foodie's paradise, offering a diverse range of culinary delights. From traditional tapas bars to Michelin-starred restaurants, there's something to satisfy every palate. Don't miss the opportunity to try local specialties like the famed Fried Squid Buns, churros, or jamón ibérico.</p>
<p>For those seeking a more laid-back experience, Madrid offers plenty of green spaces to relax and unwind. The Retiro Park is a popular spot for picnics, boating, and enjoying live music performances.</p>
<h3>Cordoba</h3>
<figure id="attachment_10289" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-10289" style="width: 830px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-10289" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/Cordoba-Plz-de-la-Corredera.jpg" alt="Plaza de la Corredera" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/Cordoba-Plz-de-la-Corredera.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/Cordoba-Plz-de-la-Corredera-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/Cordoba-Plz-de-la-Corredera-768x490.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-10289" class="wp-caption-text">Plaza de la Corredera</figcaption></figure>
<p>Tucked away in the <a href="https://spainguides.com/top-destinations/andalusia-spain/">heart of Andalusia</a>, Cordoba is a city steeped in history and culture. This charming destination offers a unique blend of Islamic and Christian influences, making it a fascinating place to explore.</p>
<p>One of Cordoba's most iconic landmarks is the Mezquita-Catedral, a stunning mosque-turned-cathedral that showcases the city's rich heritage. Wander through the intricate arches and columns of the courtyard, or admire the beautiful stained glass windows of the cathedral.</p>
<p>Beyond the Mezquita, Cordoba offers a wealth of cultural attractions. Explore the narrow streets of the Jewish Quarter, known as the Juderia, and visit the Alcazar de Los Reyes Cristianos, a former royal palace. For a taste of Andalusian cuisine, indulge in delicious tapas and local specialties at the many restaurants and bars throughout the city.</p>
<h3>San Sebastian</h3>
<figure id="attachment_15246" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-15246" style="width: 830px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-15246" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/Kursaal-Bridge.jpg" alt="Kursaal Bridge San Sebastian" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/Kursaal-Bridge.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/Kursaal-Bridge-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/Kursaal-Bridge-768x490.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-15246" class="wp-caption-text">Kursaal Bridge San Sebastian</figcaption></figure>
<p>San Sebastián is a vibrant city renowned for its stunning beaches, world-class cuisine, and lively atmosphere. This Basque gem offers a perfect blend of urban sophistication and coastal charm.</p>
<p>Indulge your taste buds with a culinary adventure in San Sebastian, a city celebrated for its<a href="https://spainguides.com/gastronomy-of-spain/san-sebastian/"> Michelin-starred Restaurants</a> and pintxo bars. Sample delicious pintxos, small savoury snacks served on slices of bread, and explore the vibrant food markets to discover local delicacies.</p>
<p>Beyond its gastronomic delights, San Sebastian offers a wealth of attractions for visitors of all ages. Explore the charming Old Town, stroll along the beachfront promenade, or take a dip in the crystal-clear waters of La Concha beach. For nature lovers, the nearby Mount Urgull offers breathtaking panoramic views of the city and bay.</p>
<p>With its friendly locals, beautiful scenery, and vibrant cultural scene, <a href="https://spainguides.com/top-destinations/san-sebastian/">San Sebastián is a must-visit destination</a> for urban travellers seeking a memorable experience.</p>
<h3>Seville</h3>
<figure id="attachment_20645" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-20645" style="width: 830px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-20645" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/Metropol-Parasol-Seville.jpg" alt="Metropol Parasol Seville" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/Metropol-Parasol-Seville.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/Metropol-Parasol-Seville-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/Metropol-Parasol-Seville-768x490.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-20645" class="wp-caption-text">Metropol Parasol Seville</figcaption></figure>
<p>Seville, the vibrant capital of Andalusia, is a city that pulsates with energy and history. With its stunning architecture, lively atmosphere, and passionate flamenco culture, Seville offers an unforgettable experience for urban travellers.</p>
<p>Explore the city's iconic landmarks, such as the <a href="https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/383/">Alcazar Palace, a UNESCO World Heritage Site</a> known for its intricate gardens and Moorish architecture. Wander through the narrow streets of the Santa Cruz neighbourhood, a charming labyrinth of whitewashed houses and courtyards.</p>
<p>For a taste of Andalusian culture, don't miss the opportunity to experience a flamenco show. Seville is renowned for its passionate flamenco dancers and musicians, who bring this expressive art form to life.</p>
<p>Indulge your taste buds with delicious tapas and local specialties like gazpacho and paella. Seville's vibrant food scene offers a variety of options to suit every palate.</p>
<p>Whether you're a history buff, a foodie, or simply looking for a fun-filled urban adventure, Seville has something to offer everyone.</p>
<h3>Valencia</h3>
<figure id="attachment_26347" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-26347" style="width: 830px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-26347" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/Town-Hall-Valencia.jpg" alt="Town Hall Valencia" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/Town-Hall-Valencia.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/Town-Hall-Valencia-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/Town-Hall-Valencia-768x490.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-26347" class="wp-caption-text">Town Hall Valencia</figcaption></figure>
<p>Valencia, a beautiful city on Spain's eastern coast, offers a perfect blend of history, culture, and modern-day charm. Its Mediterranean climate, amazing beaches, and lively atmosphere make it a popular destination for urban travellers.</p>
<p>One of Valencia's most iconic landmarks is the<a href="https://spainguides.com/city-of-arts-science-valencia/"> City of Arts and Sciences</a>, a futuristic complex designed by Santiago Calatrava. Explore its unique buildings, including the Hemisferic, the Science Museum, and the Oceanographic Aquarium.</p>
<p>For a taste of history, visit the Gothic Cathedral of Valencia, a stunning example of medieval architecture. Stroll through the historic center, admiring the beautiful plazas and colourful buildings.</p>
<p><a href="https://spainguides.com/spain-travel/best-things-to-do-in-valencia/">Valencia</a> is also known for its vibrant nightlife and lively festivals. Enjoy live music, dance, and delicious food at the many bars and restaurants throughout the city.</p>
<p>With its stunning beaches, rich history, and vibrant culture, Valencia is a must-visit destination for urban travellers seeking a memorable experience.</p>
<h3>Granada</h3>
<p><img decoding="async" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-16384" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Granada_Spain.jpg" alt="Granada Spain" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Granada_Spain.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Granada_Spain-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Granada_Spain-768x490.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /></p>
<p>Nestled in the foothills of the Sierra Nevada mountains, Granada is a city steeped in history and culture. Its Moorish heritage, stunning architecture, and vibrant atmosphere make it a must-visit destination for urban travellers.</p>
<p><a href="https://spainguides.com/alhambra-granada/">The Alhambra Palace</a>, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, is Granada's crown jewel. This magnificent palace complex offers a glimpse into the city's rich past. Explore the intricate gardens, ornate courtyards, and towering towers of the Alhambra.</p>
<p>For a taste of Andalusian culture, wander through the narrow streets of the Albaicin, Granada's historic Moorish quarter. Admire the whitewashed houses, charming plazas, and panoramic views of the city.</p>
<p><a href="https://spainguides.com/spain-travel/best-things-to-do-in-granada/">Granada</a> is also known for its lively nightlife and delicious cuisine. Enjoy free tapas, flamenco shows, and vibrant street markets.</p>
<h3>Bilbao</h3>
<p><img decoding="async" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3069" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Bilbao.jpg" alt="Bilbao River &amp; Guggenheim Museum" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Bilbao.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Bilbao-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Bilbao-768x490.jpg 768w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Bilbao-600x383.jpg 600w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /></p>
<p>Once a gritty industrial city, <a href="https://spainguides.com/top-destinations/bilbao-holidays/">Bilbao</a> has undergone a remarkable transformation in recent decades. Today, it's a vibrant urban center known for its world-class museums, stunning architecture, and lively atmosphere.</p>
<p>The Guggenheim Museum Bilbao, a masterpiece of contemporary architecture, is a must-visit attraction. Admire its iconic titanium-clad facade and explore the impressive collection of modern and contemporary art.</p>
<p>For a taste of Basque culture, wander through the charming Casco Viejo district, the city's historic center. Discover its narrow streets, traditional taverns, and beautiful plazas.</p>
<p>Bilbao is also a foodie's paradise, offering a variety of delicious Basque dishes. Sample pintxos, small savoury snacks served on slices of bread, and explore the vibrant food markets.</p>
<h3>Toledo</h3>
<figure id="attachment_22509" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-22509" style="width: 830px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="wp-image-22509 size-full" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Puerta-Bisagra-Toledo.jpg" alt="Puerta Bisagra Toledo" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Puerta-Bisagra-Toledo.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Puerta-Bisagra-Toledo-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Puerta-Bisagra-Toledo-768x490.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-22509" class="wp-caption-text">Puerta Bisagra Toledo</figcaption></figure>
<p>Toledo is a special city that you should visit at least once in your lifetime, it’s a place frozen in time oozing a fascinating history on every corner. Its historic center, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, is a labyrinth of narrow streets, ancient churches, and majestic castles.</p>
<p>The<a href="https://spainguides.com/top-destinations/toledo-holidays/"> Alcazar of Toledo,</a> a fortress that has witnessed centuries of history, is a must-visit attraction. Explore its imposing towers, beautiful courtyards, and panoramic views of the city.</p>
<p>For a taste of Toledo's rich cultural heritage, visit the Toledo Cathedral, a stunning Gothic masterpiece adorned with intricate carvings and stained glass windows.</p>
<p>Wander through the Jewish Quarter, a historic neighbourhood filled with charming cobblestone streets and ancient synagogues.</p>
<h3>Malaga</h3>
<figure id="attachment_1802" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-1802" style="width: 830px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-1802" src="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Malaga-Costa-del-Sol.jpg" alt="Malaga Costa del Sol" width="830" height="530" srcset="https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Malaga-Costa-del-Sol.jpg 830w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Malaga-Costa-del-Sol-300x192.jpg 300w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Malaga-Costa-del-Sol-768x490.jpg 768w, https://spainguides.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Malaga-Costa-del-Sol-600x384.jpg 600w" sizes="(max-width: 830px) 100vw, 830px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-1802" class="wp-caption-text">Malaga</figcaption></figure>
<p><a href="https://spainguides.com/spain-travel/best-things-to-do-in-malaga/">Malaga is the gateway to the famed Costa del Sol</a> on Spain's southern coast. Its Mediterranean climate, beautiful beaches, and lively atmosphere make it a popular destination for urban travellers.</p>
<p>One of Malaga's most iconic landmarks is the Alcazaba, a Moorish fortress that offers stunning panoramic views of the city. Explore its intricate gardens, ancient walls, and Roman Theatre.</p>
<p>For art lovers, <a href="https://www.museopicassomalaga.org/en" target="_blank" rel="noopener">the Picasso Museum</a> is a must-visit. This museum showcases the works of Pablo Picasso, one of the world's most famous artists, and offers a glimpse into his life and career.</p>
<p>Malaga's historic center is a charming labyrinth of narrow streets, colourful buildings, and traditional tapas bars. Wander through the vibrant Mercado Central, a bustling food market filled with fresh produce, seafood, and local delicacies.</p>
